{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/mecab-usage-and-add-user-dictionary-to-mecab-9ee58966fc6", "time": 1683001369.139908, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/mecab-usage-and-add-user-dictionary-to-mecab-9ee58966fc6/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "MeCab Usage and Add User Dictionary to MeCab | by Xu LIANG | Towards Data Science", "h1": "MeCab Usage and Add User Dictionary to MeCab", "description": "If you are an NLP engineer working in Japan, you mush have heard the text segmentation library, MeCab. This library is widely used in both academia and industry in Japan. And if you are a non-native\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.wikiwand.com/en/SWIG", "anchor_text": "SWIG", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://taku910.github.io/mecab/dic.html", "anchor_text": "official document", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://www.wikiwand.com/en/Vowel_length#/Phonemic_vowel_length", "anchor_text": "long vowel", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://www.wikiwand.com/en/Ruby_character", "anchor_text": "ruby", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://www.wikiwand.com/en/Vowel_length#/Phonemic_vowel_length", "anchor_text": "long vowels", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://github.com/buruzaemon/natto/wiki/Output-Formatting", "anchor_text": "EN version", "paragraph_index": 19}, {"url": "https://taku910.github.io/mecab/format.html", "anchor_text": "JP version", "paragraph_index": 19}, {"url": "https://medium.com/@bramblexu", "anchor_text": "Medium", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "https://bramblexu.com/posts/eb7bd472/", "anchor_text": "a categorized view", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "https://github.com/BrambleXu", "anchor_text": "BrambleXu", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/xu-liang-99356891/", "anchor_text": "Xu Liang", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "https://bramblexu.com", "anchor_text": "BrambleXu", "paragraph_index": 20}, {"url": "http://linkedin.com/in/xu-liang-99356891/", "anchor_text": "linkedin.com/in/xu-liang-99356891/", "paragraph_index": 22}], "all_paragraphs": ["If you are an NLP engineer working in Japan, you mush have heard the text segmentation library, MeCab. This library is widely used in both academia and industry in Japan. And if you are a non-native Japanese speaker, it might be difficult to use this tool because the documents are mostly written by Japanese. So I write this tutorial to ease the burden.", "Install MeCab and the dictionary. The mecab-python3 won\u2019t work without these dependencies.", "You can run the mecab command to try the interactive interface", "Install SWIG. We have to install this library, otherwise, there would be errors when installing mecab-python3.", "The installable is finished. We can write a script to give a try.", "According to the official document, there are 2 ways to add a customized dictionary, change the \u201csystem dictionary\u201d and add a \u201cuser dictionary\u201d. If we change the \u201csystem dictionary\u201d, we have to compile the dictionary and install it again. So we choose to add a new \u201cuser dictionary\u201d.", "First, we have to write the custom dictionary to a CSV file, the format looks like below.", "Each line contains 13 features. For example, if we want to add noun words (\u6d3b\u7528\u3057\u306a\u3044\u8a9e), like location, people\u2019s name, we could write like below.", "But if we want to add adjectives or verb (\u6d3b\u7528\u3059\u308b\u8a9e), we have to add all their conjugation type (\u6d3b\u7528\u578b) and conjugation forms (\u6d3b\u7528\u5f62). See the below example for the adjective \u201c\u3044\u305d\u304c\u3057\u3044\u201d.", "Below is a demonstration of the long vowel phenomenon.", "\u201c\u4eca\u65e5\u201d and \u201c\u52b4\u50cd\u201d are the surface form. \u201c10\u201d is the cost. Lower cost means this word has a high frequency in the corpus. \u201c\u540d\u8a5e\u201d is the POS tag. \u201c\u4e00\u822c\u201d is the sub-POS tag, which can be ignored. The final three columns represent \u201coriginal form\u201d, \u201cruby\u201d, and \u201cpronunciation\u201d. The ruby character means how a word should be pronounced. But in real conversation, people usually ignore the vowel letters (a e i o u, \u30a2\u30a4\u30a6\u30a8\u30aa in Japanse) to pronounce a word easier. This phenomenon usually occurs with long vowels.", "In the below example, \u201c\u30a6\u201d will be ignored.", "The Romanji of \u201c\u4eca\u65e5\u201d is \u201ckyou\u201d. The \u201co\u201d and \u201cu\u201d are both vowels, so this is a long vowel. When we pronounce \u201c\u4eca\u65e5\u201d, \u201cu\u201d will be ignored. So the pronunciation becomes \u201ckyo\u201d and \u201co\u201d produce as a long vowel, /u\u02d0/.", "For the following demonstration, I build a foo.csv file and input some nouns.", "Next we need to compile this CSV file.", "Make sure the user dictionary is created successfully.", "Move the foo.dic to a new directory.", "Next, we need to add the path to mecabrc file.", "If you have multiple user dictionary file, you could write them in one line.", "If I want to know the cost, we could change the output format. %m is the surface form, %c is the cost, and %H is a comma-delimited list of POS, conjugation, reading, etc. You can find more detail in these documents, EN version, and JP version.", "Check out my other posts on Medium with a categorized view!GitHub: BrambleXuLinkedIn: Xu LiangBlog: BrambleXu", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "I\u2019m an engineer focusing on NLP and Data Science. I write stuff to repay the engineer community. You can find me on linkedin.com/in/xu-liang-99356891/"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F9ee58966fc6&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operati